segments.text: Oh, the day I arrived.
And also what you got is a little tackle box.
And in this tackle box you had a set of instruments and you had your French curves and your triangles and your engineering scale and your architect scale and all that went in there.
And of course the set of pencils that you used it for.
And Cliff Ransdell was my

my second term engineering design engineering drawing describe him as a faculty as a teacher faculty member oh he was very nice and leisurely just like you know knew him too he's very kind and in fact all our teachers were i think bfk mullins i guess he was gone but he was one of the those profs there too did y'all have a nickname for rangel
I don't remember it.
I don't remember one.
No?
Economics.
Do you remember who taught economics?
No.
Al Chalk wasn't here yet, was he?
Who's that?
Al Chalk.
Chalk kind of was here.
I don't know that I had him, though.
Econ 203.
Now, I presume that your slide rule and that tackle box
was kind of the signature of an engineering student.
Oh, sure.
The slide rule was on a thing.
I've got my slide rule in there now.
Do you remember what it cost?
I don't know, $4 or $5, I guess.
Do you remember in general what that first year cost?
What your tuition was?
You mean all of our books and everything?
Oh, I can't say over $30 or $40.
We also bought
a drawing board with a handle on it.
And I think my mama might have made a case to put that thing in, a canvas or a friend did.
So we'd have that drawing board too you had to haul along, particularly back in the dorm because you did a lot of work.
My roommate Bill Atkinson finished second in his class.
He won the freshman math contest and won the national lettering
contest, and he worked hard at it.
But his sophomore year, he only got second place.
Spencer Bain?
Spencer got second place in the freshman contest, but he always throws it up to me that he got first in the sophomore class, and my roommate only got second.
As you think back about it,
Which of the courses consumed the greatest amount of time?
Well, electrical engineering courses did.
Oh, yeah.
You had a lab for each one, for one thing.
And you students were very much profession-oriented.
You were really serious about becoming electrical engineers.
Oh, I think so.
I don't know that I even should have taken electrical engineering, but I was
I'm not in a dilemma.
My sophomore year, we had Bill Atkinson in my squad, and the other guy was equally as smart, and they'd run experiments.
They didn't need to.
They were both amateur radio operators, and a lot of the double E's were hams, and that's how they got interested in electrical engineering.
So I didn't learn as much as they did, and they didn't need it either anyway, like I did.
Now, you were saying that the primary emphasis was then power.
Did you hear anything before you left for military service?
Did you hear anything that hinted about the coming events in electronics?
Well, yes, of course.
We still had just the vacuum tube, so the applications were fairly limited.
Field theory was more and more important.
And what happened in World War II, the U.S. Army and so forth did a good job of recruiting people for good discipline.
So many telephone company men got in.
They gave them direct commission to teach.
Well, anyway, my roommate and these other two that went in the Navy, they wound up at Harvard and MIT in radar.
In other words, they got the theoretical thing and
How they picked these out, I don't know.
Rodenberger, you know, I don't mean Rodenberger.
His wife is a history prof. Underberger.
Underberger.
Underberger was a physics major, and they also sent him to MIT and to Harvard because of the need for this sort of thing.
So they recruited well in that respect.
All right, let's see.
Other events.
What did the YMCA offer?
What did a student do at the YMCA?
Well, of course, freshmen couldn't go in there.
The bowling alley was in the basement.
Underneath the bowling alley was a swimming pool.
And when they built PL downs, they covered it over.
And the only reason you could go into the YMCA is go to church on Sunday.
But as a sophomore, you didn't go to YMCA?
Well, you could go in there.
I bowled in there somewhat.
But one thing that ended me is a couple of kids in there could go in there and play ping pong, and I couldn't.
Well, it was Jim Cashin and Red Cashin because their daddy was the YMCA secretary.
And they tells about how they swam in that pool.
Wow.
Now, they lived on campus.
They lived on campus.
And they were, by your standards, they were little boys, weren't they?
Yeah, they were.
See, they're five, seven years younger.
Jim was a quarterback after World War II.
He was about four or five years younger than Red, about six.
All right, I'm going to interview Red on Monday morning.
Describe for me your impression of Red and Jim as little boys.
Oh, I can't remember them other than I just remember them playing in there and
find out who they were and wondering how in the world they would get in there to play.
So you don't remember any mischief?
No, not really.
Incidentally, with WTAW, the transmitter was in Bolton Hall and the studio was on the second floor of the YMCA.
And they had antennas on each of those buildings with the wire in between.
And Dutch Dillingham
He got pictures of him way back there in the 30s, and of course the first broadcast of a game was on WTAW and this sort of thing.
All right, now it was operated in that day, operated by A&M, by the electrical engineering department?
No, by students, so N-double-E.
But it was, of course, a university station even then.
What kind of programs did they have?
I can't remember, really.
They just played music as far as I know.
Did they do football games in your day?
Or did Kern Tips do them?
Oh, Kern Tips did them.
Oh, yeah.
WTAW has gotten away from that then.
Oh, yeah.
Umbel Oil and Refining Company.
What kind of music did they play?
I can't remember that either, but I'm sure it's the popular music of the day.
Glenn Miller and Harry James and people like that.
All right, let's see.
Guyon Hall was the auditorium.
Tell me about, describe some events you remember occurring in Guyon Hall.
Well, of course, at that time, we had Math 101.
They all took the math final exam at the same time.
So they would put us all in Gine Hall, and this was even true when I came back and started teaching in 56.
They still had exams, a common exam for one course, and they'd spread us out in Gine Hall.
And, of course, we had the Holy Week or Religious Emphasis Week in the spring, and so each day you would have a program there.
And they would dismass classes so you could go to these.
Was there good turnout for those?
Oh, I think there was, yeah.
I don't know that I ever went.
I grew up a Christian scientist.
And we had our little services up on the second floor of the YMCA.
How many attended that Christian Science?
Oh, I'd say maybe five or ten.
And one of the students was the reader.
Were there any other, and let me call that as a non-mainline denomination, were there any other religious groups that had meetings here that weren't mainline denominations?
I don't think so.
Oh, I can't remember.
The Presbyterians met in the YMCA.
The Methodists had a kind of an old barn up there where they are now.
The Catholics have an old chapel on the corner.
And that was it.
Uh-huh.
Do you remember any Jewish students when you were here?
Well, of course, the Hillel Foundation was quite strong.
And we, I think, had a real good representation
of the Jewish community and they were right into the rest of us.
I can't say where and when they went.
Do you remember, do you have any recollection, what was the respect and or toleration of the different religious groups?
How did Aggies feel about someone else's religious affiliation?
Oh, I don't think we had any prejudices at all particularly.
We weren't very religious, most of us, I would say.
Were there some Hispanic students in your, in your?
Yeah, we had three or four, yeah.
And did they have certain special nicknames?
No, they were just one of the, one of the students, yeah.
What about some international students?
Were there some from other countries?
Very little, I don't know.
The Zuniga, he was from,

the way to Laredo, and I got him to come back after 50 years, and De La Chica, I don't know, he stayed around for a while, yeah, but I, other than that, Martinez was a sophomore, we didn't like him, and his roommate was Jewish, but that didn't make any difference, yeah.
Let's see, do you remember any notable celebrities that came to the campus in those pre-war years?
Well, of course, the one we had, we've never been licked while you had all that, Wallace Berry Jr. and Jim Mitchell, or what is his name, Mitchum?
Robert Mitchum.
Robert Mitchum, and then the third one and the two women.
I've got the tape of the thing, too, and we were in that thing, of course.
Describe the campus excitement about that.
When we had them here, we spent a lot of time
out on the drill field, just more or less having reviews and this sort of thing.
And it hardly got into the film at all.
But the hero in this thing was in disgrace, kind of.
And in my outfit, we marched right up a military walk up into Sabisa Dining Hall.
And so...
And it was my outfit that tripped him as he went up the stairs.

What happened was he had, this hero had grown up in Japan and he came to school late and all that stuff and he finally got with it and that sort of thing and his senior year he has boots and this sort of thing.
But he kind of defended the Japanese because he had lived there.
Well, this made him, of course, Persia non grata and all that stuff.
It didn't have anything to do with him.
As I say, they tripped him as he went up the steps.
And then he went on over to Japan and became a Japanese broadcaster and so forth.
And he got on an aircraft carrier, and he sat behind the pilots.
And he heard his roommate, which was Wallace Berry Jr., told him he was.
And so he choked the Japanese pilot and caused the plane to crash into the Japanese carrier.
And so they awarded him the Congressional Medal of Honor, and he had his boots at my coffee, and that sort of thing.
That was really the corniest movie I think I ever saw.
Where did all those movie stars stay?
when they were here?
I guess they put them up in the Aggieland Inn, right across the street from Sbisa Hall.
They were here weeks?
Were they here weeks?
Months?
Oh, they didn't stay very long.
No, just the external scenes and also in the Sbisa Hall where they danced, but all of the indoor scenes were back in Hollywood.
And even the stuff where he got onto the horse drone, field artillery, they were all back in Hollywood.
Obviously, they weren't here from the terrain they were in.
Other celebrities before you went away to the war, did the big bands come here and play during that?
Oh, definitely.
Oh, yeah.
And of course, what you had in the spring, you had a regimental ball on Friday night where a certain regiment
had their ball, and then Saturday night was the core dance.
So they played for both nights.
And we had Glenn Miller and Harry James and any number of the big-name orchestras came here.
And these were in Sabisa?
In Sabisa, the main dining hall of Sabisa.
That's the only place there.
I think we might have had one over here in the new area on one side of the dining hall at the core area.
Did you have a date come down?
Oh, yeah, I had a date, and I went and got a car, got folks' car that weekend, so I went up and brought my date back, and also a friend in the outfit, his date, and I also brought back her mother.
I didn't intend for that to happen, but we put them up over in blue bonnet cores.
You know, the building where the restaurant is right next to Jones Pharmacy now.
It's a cottage type, so that's where I had to put them up.
How was a young woman treated at an Aggie dance?
At a dance?
You couldn't dance with her.
I mean, always, if somebody was always cutting in, you'd bring your date, and you didn't get to dance with her very much because most of us didn't have dates.
And so here we were, and so you kept cutting in all the time.
You could never dance a whole night, a whole date, a whole dance with one person.
But were the girls treated like royalty?
Oh, I think so.
And of course, we vacated one of the dormitories, and they stayed in that dormitory, and we found out where we could stay anywhere on the campus.
You didn't have enough room.
Some of them stayed off campus in
in the faculty housing and on campus and so forth.
But by and large, that's where we had to put them up.
Was there much drinking at an Aggie dance?
No, not at all.
I don't believe at all.
You might have a drink ahead of time,
There were no tables around.
You had chairs all the way around.
Strictly dancing.
We had lots of chaperones, the faculty wives and so forth.
And every student was in uniform?
Yeah.
The only people that didn't wear a uniform were graduate students.
And they didn't participate in that.
We didn't have many graduate students either.
And also, a lot of them wore uniform.
They had to, anyway.
So we didn't have much graduate school.
Were there any, talking about celebrities coming, were there any important national leaders who came before you went away to the war?
Well, of course, President Roosevelt came.
Did he?
During the war, yeah.
Did you get to see him?
I just remember he was here.
I'm not sure what year it was.
I do remember Dutch Dillingham saying that he got a really good PA system
for him when he was out on Carl Field.
And then he said Roosevelt knew exactly how to handle it, but, you know, keeping feedback, he'd say something, take it out of the way.
He knew not to get the feedback.
So he was a very accomplished speaker.
Describe in those pre-war, pre-going away to the war year, describe the routine of a football, home football Saturday.
What time did things begin?
Well, you had midnight yell practice the night before, but the games were all in the afternoon.
Where was midnight yell practice held?
Midnight yell practice, was that held at the Y?
That was in front of the YMCA.
Later on, they moved it over in front of Goodman Hall.
It had more room there.
But as soon as the meal was over, we went over to the stadium.
The freshmen sat in front, sophomores, juniors, and seniors.
We didn't march in.
You're talking about the noon meal.
After the noon meal, we immediately went over and got us a good seat.
And so we didn't march in or anything at all like that.
And after the game was over, if we won, we went back over to the YMCA and had another yell practice.
And did y'all throw the yell-eaters in the?
No.
That wasn't?
No, no, that wasn't in it at all.
Did anybody ever tear down a goal post?
Never did that.
Oh, no, they didn't feel like that.
And did you ever have, did you have many dates for a football game?
I only had, that date I was, and then also I had a girl who got over here from Austin,
And so we took them to the dance, and they wanted to go out to Uncle Ed's.
So we took them out to Uncle Ed Hard Liquor.
You familiar with it?
Now, that was on Welborn Road?
Welborn Road, just about where Luther hits it.
It's kind of on the corner there.
It's still there.
It's a little Chinese place, one story, about a half mile south of George Bush.
So we took them out there because, you know, it was famous from a song, and it was a mess.
It really was awful.
The gals didn't like it.
They wanted to go, though.
They knew about it, so we took them out there.
Now, beer, was beer available there?
Was what now?
Beer.
Was there any beer and hard liquors?
Oh, yeah, beer.
Beer was the only thing you could get in the county.
But not whiskey?
No, no hard liquor.
No, no, no.
There was hard liquor out there, but no whiskey.
And did he serve food?
I think so.
What was it?
We just went out there to drink beer, though.
The girls didn't drink beer.
About how many people could Mr. Hard Liquor's place accommodate?
Hard liquor?
Not very many.
I would say you couldn't get 100 people in there, even that much.
Was it ever rowdy?
Routy over what?
Was it ever rowdy?
Were there fights?
Not at all.
I didn't really go out there, but it was really just a place to drink beer.
Because I've heard mention of Uncle Ed's, a great day.
Yeah, drank our troubles away.
Let's see, midnight yell practice, were there silver taps?
Oh yeah, we had those once, twice a year, but we didn't kill many Aggies.
Do you remember your feelings as you went to your first Silver Taps events?
Oh, I can certainly remember it, and it was a very solemn occasion.
That's about all I could say about it.
Was Aggie, was Muster held before the war that you remember?
Yes, it was.
Of course, it became famous during the war, but I... Where was it held?
I can't remember where the muster was held.
Let's see, after that first summer, did you have a job at home?
For the summer, I got a job for a quarter of an hour out of Seville.
They were building a new federal prison out there, and I had a friend who helped me get the job.
So we put together storage cabinets at 25 cents an hour.
That's about the only job I had that summer.
And that didn't relate much to electrical engineering?
No, it sure didn't.
There's hardly any jobs like that available at all.
That was the summer of 40.
Of 40.
What about the next summer?
The next summer, I went to summer school one of the times, yeah.
Describe the community of College Station.
What was there around the campus then, housing and so forth?
How big was the?
Well, of course, when you crossed the stop sign up here, Park Place,
There was nothing this side of it, even when we moved here back in 1956.
It stopped at Park Place, except for the Knoll out there.
And I really can't remember much of all the houses on campus.
I remember that, the PMS&T, and of course Gilchrist was living in that house.
It's a brick house, one story.
He was there.
He was dean of engineering, man.
That's about all I can remember.
I think the student engineer's council would go over there and meet with him once in a while.
And the Northgate area, what was there?
Well, of course, on each of the corners was a drug store, and there were two or three barber shops.
Lupo was kind of down towards the campus, and that was about all there was to it.
That first block was all there was to the north gate of the business district.
The Baptists, I don't know when they built their church.
The Church of Christ was there, and as I say, the Methodist church was just a big old barn.
The railroad station I know was active.
Where was the bus station?
The what now?
The bus station.
Where did you catch the bus?
Well, of course, the bus came up to the Aggieland Inn.
The Greyhound bus drove up there to pick up passengers.
So that's where you came from.
And the post office, where did you get your mail?
Okay, where the Trigon is, and this side of it is now that utility building.
When they built the new dorms, they put a post office there, too.
And they had a little confectionery, too, so that's where our post office boxes were.
And if you wanted to buy a Coca-Cola or anything like that during the day, where would you go?
You'd have to go over there.
That was the nearest place.
Of course, the upperclassmen had concessions in the dorm, too.
They had something to sell, I can't remember.
Do you remember where you were when you heard the news of Pearl Harbor?
I was at Guyon Hall watching a movie.
And when we came out, we got the news.
How did, did a friend tell you?
Word of mouth.
We got around, you know.
And what did you and your friends do then?
Well, we had, one of our friends, we had a kind of a dormitory communication system.
could get on the radio, and he got on there like he was a Japanese and started talking about what was happening and all that stuff.
So that was the main thing.
Of course, we really realized what was happening.
Did you and your buddies know where Pearl Harbor was?
Oh, I don't know.
Hawaiian Island, that's all.
I was a sixth grader, and I remember we had to have it explained to us, of course.
were there any other, in those first three years here, were there any other events that kind of stopped you and your buddies in your tracks?
After Pearl Harbor?
No, I don't really believe we were, because D-Day, of course, was after we had all gone, just following it, the progress of it, we
And I know for me, the death of Franklin Roosevelt in 1944.
Let's see.
We're still talking about the pre-war years.
The average student, was there much beer consumed by students then?
There was a lot of liquor consumed on the dorms.
You know, they'd bring a bottle in and drink and this sort of thing.
A fair amount of that.
My first drink, I went over to White Way Cafe, which is about where 7-Eleven is, and that's where I got my first beer.
And then we walked back over to the camp and had a few beers, and that was it.
Did many students get drunk?
No, I don't think a whole lot of it.
All right, so beer, whiskey.
What about tobacco?
Did many students smoke?
Oh, we had plenty of smokers.
Oh, yeah.
And chewing tobacco?
I don't think so, no.
Snuff?
I can't remember that they had that at all.
Did you and your buddies know of any other indulgences?
I don't believe there's anything at all in the way of drugs or anything like that.
Did you even know the words?
No, I don't really think we did.
Marijuana we called Mary Jane.
When I was a kid in the park in Dallas, you'd talk about Mary Jane a little bit.
Did you ever see any Mary Jane?
No.
That's what they called marijuana, though.
Let's see.
Court trip.
Describe court trip during those falls.
Well, of course, if it was in Houston, we'd hitchhike and spend the night before
in a downtown hotel, and then for the rice game, of course, we would march in Houston.
I do remember staying in the Cotton Hotel and getting pretty drunk there, you know, away from home and this sort of thing.
Of course, Dallas and Fort Worth was my home in Dallas, so we'd just stay at home.
Did you have a few guests at your house then?
No, not really, uh-uh.
Either Dallas or Fort Worth would be one of the other games for SSMU or TCU.
And Waco, we didn't march in Waco.
You know why we no longer marched in Waco, yeah.
Let's see.
There was a court trip to Austin.
In Austin, we were.
And I had a high school roommate in the dorm there, so I slept on the floor.
And, of course, after that,
40 game and we lost, we were going to spend the night.
But after we lost, we got out of town.
I got a high school classmate and we just high-tailed up at Waco and stopped for supper.
And then a goofy guy, he got over on the left-hand side, a car came the other way and hit us on the rear.
And I was in the back rear seat and we went over and turned over on our side and
And this car that came behind us got over on the other side and the guy was killed in that thing.
We hauled, they hauled the car in and we had to hitchhike home.
Back to that 1940 game in Austin.
I described the feelings of the Aggies in the... We just stood up in the grand and cried.
Like babies, no fooling.
We were going to the Rose Bowl.
He already had the invitations.

A number of years later, old Homer Norton's daughter was with us on the way to Mexico with my wife for Spanish, and we drove by there, and I told her, I said, this is the saddest place your daddy ever experienced in that stadium there.
Of course, he had that place across the street and his wife.
Did you students have any impression of him in his coaching days here?
Homer Norton?
Oh, not particularly.
I guess he's kind of autocratic, I guess.
I can't say more than that.

Like one of the things I learned from Barney Welch that causes me, in hindsight, to respect Coach Norton, Barney said that Coach Norton promised every single athlete that had a scholarship who went away to the war, when you come back, you will have a scholarship.
And he said what hurt was that he kept his word
And some of those were not that good as athletes four years later.
But he kept his word.
Barney was pretty good.
